description.narrative: (Cambodia): The Cambodia Countering Trafficking-in-Persons (CCTIP) activity seeks to mitigate TIP risk factors by reducing unsafe labor migration, which, in turn, increases vulnerability to debt slavery and other forms of exploitation, and also protects and assists the victims of trafficking. With FY 2018 funds, the CCTIP activity will implement preventive measures, focusing on root causes of trafficking relating to education, employment opportunities, and livelihoods and strengthen TIP survivor protection services by enhancing victim identification and delivering services that help trafficking victims reintegrate into society. The CCTIP activity's preventive measures also include expanding clean water availability as a means of improving livelihoods in areas at higher risk for trafficking. As this activity supports victim's rights, it aligns with Mission Objective 1.2 (CDCS DO1) "Strengthen credible voices to promote fundamental democratic principles and human rights, " and addresses the Administration priority to "Advance American Influence" (National Security Strategy, Pillar IV) by addressing the underlying conditions causing people to fall victim to human trafficking. In addition, this activity is critical to meeting the Administration priority of "Aligning U.S. national security objectives" by addressing the underlying conditions contributing to irregular migration to the United States. The activity was competitively awarded based on the best value to the U.S. government, in accordance with federal procurement regulations.
